[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(19) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Brethren.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "My brethren, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "it rather ought to be. The last, and, to some, the dearest of the wise Apostle’s remarks, is this on conversion; and it fitly closes his loving and plain-speaking Letter.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If any of you do err . . .—Better thus, If one of you be led away from the truth, and one convert him. It is not the wilful error, so much as the being seduced by others, who draw the unwary from their proper course, till in time they become of themselves “wandering stars, to whom is reserved the blackness of darkness for ever” (Jude 1:13). As the leading away was an act prompted by the devil, so the bringing home is the service of God, and each will have its fit reward. The sinner is riding, as it were, headlong to destruction, when a friend lays hold upon the rein, and literally “converts” him, i.e., turns him round; but, observe, the wanderer is still far from home, and many a weary league must he traverse, even with face turned and kept heavenward, before the end be neared.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "If any of you do err . . .",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Better thus, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "If one of you be led away from the truth, and one convert him.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " It is not the wilful error, so much as the being seduced by others, who draw the unwary from their proper course, till in time they become of themselves “wandering stars, to whom is reserved the blackness of darkness for ever” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jude 1:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). As the leading away was an act prompted by the devil, so the bringing home is the service of God, and each will have its fit reward. The sinner is riding, as it were, headlong to destruction, when a friend lays hold upon the rein, and literally “converts” him, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "i.e., ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "turns him round; but, observe, the wanderer is still far from home, and many a weary league must he traverse, even with face turned and kept heavenward, before the end be neared.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "James 5:19-20",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "James 5:19-20",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Brethren ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— As if he had said, I have now warned you of those things to which you are most liable. And in all these respects watch, not only over yourselves, but every one over his brother also. Labour, in particular, to recover those that are fallen. For ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "if any of you do err from the truth ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— From the right way in which he ought to walk, if he be seduced by any means from the doctrine and practice of the gospel; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "one ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Any one; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "convert him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Be a means of bringing him back into that way from which he had wandered; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "let him know ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Who has been enabled to effect so good a work; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "that he who converteth a sinner from the error of his way ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— From the false doctrine and bad practice to which he had turned aside, shall produce a much happier effect than any miraculous cure of the body; for he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "shall save a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "precious immortal ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "soul from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "spiritual and eternal ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "death, and shall hide a multitude of sins ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Namely, the sins of the persons thus converted, which shall no more, how many soever they are, be remembered to his condemnation. “The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "covering of sin ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "is a phrase which often occurs in the Old Testament, and always signifies the pardoning of sin. Nor has it any other meaning here. For surely it cannot be the apostle’s intention to tell us, that the turning of a sinner from the error of his way will conceal from the eye of God’s justice a multitude of sins committed by the person who does this charitable office, if he continueth in them. Such a person needs himself to be turned from the error of his way, in order that his own soul may be saved from death. St. Peter has a similar expression, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "love covereth a multitude of sins; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "not, however, in the person who is possessed of love, but in the person who is the object of his love.” — Macknight. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
